If you want to support both static linking of plugins in the game executable and dynamic loading of plugins in the editor, you can use preprocessor directives in your code.

For example, you can define a `STATIC_PLUGINS` preprocessor directive when building the game executable, which tells the code to include the plugins statically. Then, in your code, you can use `#if` and `#endif` statements to include code that is specific to the static plugin implementation.

On the other hand, when building the editor executable, you can exclude the `STATIC_PLUGINS` preprocessor directive, which tells the code to load the plugins dynamically. In this case, you can use `#if` and `#endif` statements to include code that is specific to the dynamic plugin implementation.

Here is some example code to illustrate this concept:

```csharp
// Define a preprocessor directive for static plugins when building the game executable
#define STATIC_PLUGINS

// Define a common interface that plugins should implement
public interface IPlugin
{
    void Update();
}

// Define a static plugin implementation
#if STATIC_PLUGINS
public class MyPlugin : IPlugin
{
    public void Update()
    {
        // Update the plugin
    }
}

// Register the static plugin at startup
static void Main()
{
    MyPlugin plugin = new MyPlugin();
    // Register the plugin with the game code
}
#endif

// Define a dynamic plugin implementation
#if !STATIC_PLUGINS
public class DynamicPlugin : IPlugin
{
    public void Update()
    {
        // Update the plugin
    }
}

// Load and register the dynamic plugin at runtime
public void LoadPlugin(string path)
{
    Assembly assembly = Assembly.LoadFrom(path);
    Type type = assembly.GetType("DynamicPlugin");
    IPlugin plugin = (IPlugin)Activator.CreateInstance(type);
    // Register the plugin with the editor code
}
#endif
```

Note how the `MyPlugin` class is only defined and registered when the `STATIC_PLUGINS` preprocessor directive is defined, while the `DynamicPlugin` class is only defined and loaded when the directive is not defined.

By using preprocessor directives and including code that is specific to the type of plugin implementation, you can support both static linking in the game executable and dynamic loading in the editor.
